Date: Thu 22 Dec 2011
Source: Leyte Samar Daily Express [edited]
http://leytesamardaily.net/2011/12/cassava-disease-outbreak-in-e-visayas-reported/


Cassava disease outbreak in E. Visayas
--------------------------------------
An outbreak of a disease, predicted to cut cassava output in Eastern
Visayas by at least 50 percent in 2011/2012, is spreading, the
Philippine Root Crop Research and Training Center (PhilRootcrops) has
warned.

Erlinda Vasquez, PhilRootcrops, said a large number of phytoplasma
[infections] known as witches' broom has been discovered in 70
hectares of cassava in Leyte and Southern Leyte. They are also
investigating reports that 3 Samar provinces have also been affected.

"The disease will place a huge strain on cassava production," Vasquez
said. "It will affect the incomes of small farmers and many laborers.
Cassava is one of the staple foods in Eastern Visayas and is also
processed into animal feed."

PhilRootcrops has issued preliminary management guidelines to help
tackle the outbreaks. The spread is almost certainly caused by the
movement of infected planting material. "Our immediate response is to
impose strict quarantine regulations on the movement of cassava,
especially the stems used as planting material," Vasquez said. Farmers
were also advised to observe proper sanitation by maintaining a
debris-free field.

"At present, we are conducting exhaustive surveys to cover the entire
region to completely determine the infected areas," Vasquez said.

[Byline: Reyan L Arinto]

