Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
promed@promedmail.org

[Witches' broom disease of cassava is caused by Cassava witches' broom
phytoplasma (synonym Cassava phyllody phytoplasma; _Candidatus_
Phytoplasma asteris group). It can seriously affect starch content of
tubers, and yield losses up to 80 percent have been reported in the
Americas. Symptoms may include excessive proliferation of branches
('witch's brooms'), small leaves, shortened internodes, purple
discolouration of 'brooms,' stunting and loss of plant vigour.
Characteristically, shoot distortion or leaf chlorosis are not
normally observed. Tubers are reduced in size with rough textured skin
and brown streaks in the flesh. Moderate temperatures between 13 and
20 degC favour disease development, symptoms become less obvious or
even disappear at higher temperatures.

The disease is mainly spread by vegetative propagation of the crop.
Mechanical transmission has also been reported, but no insect vectors
are known. Disease management relies on the use of certified clean
planting material. Thermotherapy followed by meristem tip culture can
be used to obtain phytoplasma-free tissue culture lines for
propagation.

